Department of Energy Western Area Power Administration Rocky Mountain Customer Service Region P.O. Box 3700 Loveland, CO 80539-3003
Letter Agreement No. 11-RMR-2269 (Installation of Boundary Meter at Bijou)
Mr. Ian R. Benson Director, Transmission Business Relations and Asset Management Xcel Energy Services, Inc. 414 Nicollet Mall - MP08 Minneapolis, MN 55401
Dear Mr. Benson:
Public Service Company of Colorado (Public Service) submitted an Application for a Boundary Meter at Bijou, along with a Five Thousand Dollar ($5,000) deposit to the Western Area Power Administration (Western). The location of the boundary meter is from the Bijou Substation (Morgan County Rural Electric Association) on the northeast 12.5-kV circuit (see enclosed drawing). The Bijou boundary meter (Boundary Meter) will be between the Western Area Colorado Missouri and Public Service’s Balancing Authorities.
In accordance with and subject to the provisions of this Letter Agreement No. 11RMR2269 (Letter Agreement) between Western and Public Service (collectively called the Parties), the Parties agree that the requested work will be performed under the following terms and conditions:
Western, at the sole expense of Public Service, shall:
Review schematics, wiring diagrams, panel layouts, configurations, points list, test reports, and nameplate data for all meter system equipment.
Reserve the right to witness the installation, inspection, testing, and calibration of the metering equipment and to be present when metering facilities are modified. Western requires an electronic pdf formatted Meter Test Report within thirty (30) days of any meter test.
Carry the Bijou metering data over the existing channel used for the Public Service Beaver Creek Substation boundary meter data. Western currently carries this data from Public Service’s Beaver Creek Substation to Western’s boundary metering master via a Western-owned 4/W modem located in Public Service’s Beaver Creek Substation.
Adjust Western’s Automatic Generation Control (AGC) program to exclude the portion associated with the Bijou load.
Program and configure the D200 at Cheyenne Substation with the new points.
Public Service, at its sole expense, shall:
Provide to Western for review: the Bijou single line and switching diagrams; metering panel layout; nameplate data; configuration data; and wiring diagrams of all the metering system equipment, including the Boundary Meter, current transformers (CTs) and potential transformers (PTs); metering Remote Terminal Unit (RTU); auxiliary metering equipment; and communication equipment.
Procure all necessary materials and equipment to install a radio link between Bijou and Public Service’s Beaver Creek Substation in support of this project.
Integrate the Boundary Meter data with the existing Public Service Beaver Creek boundary meter data, and provide the Bijou data on the RTU port that currently provides Public Service’s Beaver Creek data to Western.
Provide to Western as-built drawings thirty (30) days after any field changes or modifications.
Provide an alternate data source (ADS) for the primary boundary meter that is not connected to the same CT circuit as the Boundary Meter, such as from a breaker relay-quality CT source, or provide an ICCP value for Bijou.
Adjust Public Service’s AGC to include the portion associated with the Bijou load.
Provide to Western: all meter configuration data required to operate the MV90 meter data management system; nameplate data of the Boundary Meter; all metering RTU configuration data, and points list.
Provide the manufacturer’s CT and PT test reports for metering quality accuracy.
Provide communication access to Western for the Boundary Meter for Western’s MV-90 system or provide MV-90 data files to Western for the Boundary Meter within the first five (5) days of each month for the previous month’s data.
Perform metering calibration.
Program and configure the telemetry RTU and the SCADA RTU with the required data points.
Provide Western copies of the initial meter test report and subsequent meter test report for every maintenance interval.
Notify Western’s Outage Coordinator ten (10) business days in advance of the date and time of meter testing.
Western and Public Service, shall:
Commission the Boundary Meter.
Test the AGC values and ADS meter data with each operations center.
Energy Accounting Impact: Once in service, the Boundary Meter will have the following impact on Western’s future energy accounting:
Public Service’s Bijou kWh Boundary Meter data will be included in Public Service’s Loveland Area Projects Network Integration Transmission Service (NITS) billing.
Public Service’s Bijou Boundary Meter data will be removed from the Regulation and Frequency Response Service calculation done in conjunction with Public Service’s NITS calculation in Section 4.1
Public Service’s Bijou Boundary Meter data will be adjusted within Public Service’s Energy Imbalance Service calculation as follows: the calculation will capture transmission losses only for this meter, which will be included in the calculations of Public Service’s total hourly load.
Payment:
Public Service advanced to Western the sum of Five Thousand Dollars ($5,000) for the work to be performed by Western in Section 1. The Five Thousand Dollars ($5,000) is only an estimate.
In the event the costs, including allocable expenses, are greater than the amount advanced by Public Service, Public Service shall pay Western the difference on demand. Western shall not be required to perform any work pursuant to this Letter Agreement until additional funds have been received. If the total cost to Western is less than the amount advanced by Public Service, Western shall refund the difference without any interest whatsoever as soon as the necessary vouchers can be prepared.
Ownership, Maintenance, and Replacement: Public Service will own, maintain, replace, and have financial responsibility for the meter, radio, antenna, and any other equipment associated with this project.
License:
Public Service, under the terms and conditions specified herein, hereby grants to Western, its employees, agents, and contractors, a license to enter Public Service’s easements and rights-of-way (ROW) to accomplish the work provided for in this Letter Agreement, providing proper advance arrangements are made with Public Service.
Western, under the terms and conditions specified herein, hereby grants to Public Service, its employees, agents, and contractors, a license to enter Western’s easements and ROW to accomplish the work provided for in this Letter Agreement, providing proper advance arrangements are made with Western.
Each Party hereby grants to the other Party a license for the work to be performed under this Letter Agreement.
Operation, maintenance and replacement, and removal of facilities by any Party under the licenses granted herein shall be coordinated with the other Party to eliminate or minimize interference with the operation and maintenance of the transmission system or facilities of the other Party.
General Power Contract Provisions: The General Power Contract Provisions effective September 1, 2007, enclosed hereto, are hereby made a part of this Letter Agreement the same as if they had been expressly set forth herein; Provided, That Provisions 2 through 5, 7 through 9, and 11 through 19 shall not be applicable hereunder; Provided further, That the word Contractor in the General Power Contract Provisions refers to Public Service.
Term: This Letter Agreement shall become effective on the date signed by Public Service and shall terminate one (1) year from its effective date, Provided, That all work described herein has been completed, including the payment of all bills, and the provisions for the ownership, maintenance, replacement, and financial responsibilities have been incorporated into Exhibit 1 of Contract No. 87-LAO-337, between Western and Public Service, or other contract as applicable.
If the above provisions are satisfactory, please sign both originals of this Letter Agreement and return one original to the attention of Susan Steshyn.
Sincerely,
/S/ Bradley S. Warren
Bradley S. Warren Regional Manager
Accepted this 27th day of January, 2012

Appendix 1 to Attachment O
The formula set forth in Attachment O shall be implemented in accordance with the following principles:
A. Effective July 1, 2011, the return on common equity (“ROE”) shall be 10.25%, as established pursuant to a FERC-approved settlement in Public Service Company of Colorado, Docket No. ER11-2853-000. Xcel Energy or Public Service Company of Colorado (“PSCo”) shall be free to seek a change in the ROE under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act (“FPA”). Any PSCo Transmission Customer shall be free to seek a change in ROE through the filing of a complaint pursuant to Section 206 of the FPA.
B. Notwithstanding anything else to the contrary in the proposed formula rate or as otherwise modified by this Appendix 1 to the Attachment O, the intent of the PSCo formula is to exclude from the cost basis for transmission service charges those items that the Commission has found, by final non-appealable order binding on PSCo, are not related to the transmission function or includible in transmission rates.
C. The transmission rate formula used to determine transmission service rates and charges for PSCo shall provide for the recovery of actual SFAS 106 costs for Post-Retirement Benefits other than Pensions (“PBOPs”) booked to A&G Account 926; provided that in any year in which such costs for PSCo exceed prior year costs booked to Account 926 by more than five percent (5%), Xcel Energy will make a filing with the FERC to obtain authority to collect the current year's PBOP costs through the transmission rate formula if any transmission service customer who was a party to Docket No. ER04-1174-000 so demands. Pending a final Commission decision on such filing, such costs shall be recovered through formula-determined rates and charges but shall be subject to refund with interest in the event and to the extent that the Commission disallows such recovery. The actual PBOP costs are developed from a third-party actuarial study. As part of the AFRR Process conducted pursuant to Appendix 2 to Attachment O, Xcel Energy shall provide the network service Transmission Customers of PSCo and any Transmission Customer then taking long-term firm point-to-point service on the PSCo system under the Xcel Energy OATT the actuarial support for each year's PBOP costs in support of the annual formula calculation and a spreadsheet showing the calculation of the change for PSCo in the current year's PBOP costs included in Account 926 compared to the Account 926 bookings of such costs in the previous year.
D. Customer Contributions in Aid of Construction (“CIAC”) and prepayments for transmission facilities and PSCo allowance for funds used during construction (“AFUDC”) practices.
1. PSCo shall not book AFUDC on transmission facilities under construction that are funded by customer CIACs when the CIACs are received in advance of the incurrence of the associated construction expenditures.
2. PSCo shall not book AFUDC on transmission facilities under construction where a customer makes refundable prepayments for such facilities when such prepayments are received in advance of the incurrence of the associated construction expenditures.
3. PSCo shall reduce transmission plant in service included in rate base by an amount equal to (a) the unrefunded amounts of refundable customer prepayments for transmission facilities less (b) the sum of (i) the income tax gross-up component of such prepayments to the extent paid or an amount based on the composite income tax factor in the transmission formula rates times the prepayment if no tax gross up is allowed to the extent income tax is determined to be owed; and (ii) the transmission accumulated depreciation reserve associated with such unrefunded prepayments. The calculation will be made on a worksheet provided annually as support for the transmission formula inputs and reflect end of year amounts. The amounts in (a) and (b) shall appear as separate line items in the formula.
4. PSCo shall also include in such worksheet the cumulative interest accrued on refundable customer prepayments for transmission facilities as well as the amortization over 10 years of the accrued interest. The unamortized balance of such interest shall be included as an addition to rate base as a separate line item in the transmission formula and the annual amortization of the interest expense will be included as an expense in a separate line item in the transmission formula.
E. Transmission Rate Base.
1. Each year the formula is in effect, PSCo will prepare the transmission rates and charges to be made effective as of June 1 of the current calendar year based on December 31 rate base balances found in the PSCo Form 1 annual report for the prior calendar year.
2. The cost of generator interconnection facilities and the associated accumulated depreciation reserve associated with PSCo-owned generation facilities installed after March 15, 2000, that in accordance with FERC policy or precedent are to be directly assigned to PSCo shall be excluded from transmission rate base.
3. Common Plant for PSCo shall exclude Account 302 – Franchise and Consents and the associated accumulated depreciation/amortization reserve for such items. Common plant otherwise permitted in rate base shall be distributed between departmental operations (i.e., electric, natural gas, thermal energy and non-utility operations) using the same allocation methods that Xcel Energy used in preparing the PSCo FERC Form No. 1 Annual Report for 2004 until PSCo files with the FERC a change in the formula to use a different common plant allocation method.
4. To the extent PSCo enters into arrangements with independent power producers, including wind facilities (“IPPs”), under which the IPP does not pay for all of the Interconnection Customer or Transmission Provider Interconnection Facilities (as defined in the Xcel Energy OATT) as may otherwise be required by Commission policy or order, costs of such interconnection facilities not recovered from the IPP shall not be included in the PSCo transmission rate base in the formula.
5. PSCo shall include items from common plant accounts that relate to customer information systems and the associated accumulated depreciation/amortization reserve for such items.
6. If consistent with FERC ratemaking policy, gross plant investment and associated accumulated depreciation reserves for generator step-up transformers shall, for purposes of applying the formula, be refunctionalized from the transmission function to the production function; otherwise no refunctionalization of plant to the transmission function shall be permitted in applying the formula unless effected by changes in accounting procedures that are approved by the FERC or its staff under delegation of authority or that are otherwise consistent with FERC ratemaking policy. Nothing in Attachment H or in Attachment O and its Appendices shall be deemed to prohibit or condition in any way the right of Xcel Energy or PSCo, or any of their affiliates, to seek a regulatory determination that particular plant items should be classified for accounting or ratemaking purposes in a manner different from that permitted by the Uniform System of Accounts.
7. No costs associated with Phase II of the DC Tie shall be included in the PSCo transmission rates and charges used beginning June 1, 2005, for the billing year June 1, 2005-May 31, 2006. Costs associated with Phase II of the DC Tie will be reflected in rates effective June 1, 2006. For the billing year June 1, 2006 to May 31, 2007, 63% of the PSCo Phase II DC Tie costs shall be included in the formula transmission rate base in determining rates to be made effective on June 1, 2006. For the billing years June 1, 2007 to May 31, 2008 and thereafter, 100% of the PSCo Phase II DC Tie costs shall be included in the formula transmission rate base in determining rates to be made effective on June 1, 2007, and on June 1 of subsequent billing years for similar billing periods, in each case based on actual Phase II DC Tie costs recorded on PSCo's books and records in the previous calendar year.
8. Changes in depreciation rates shall be given effect as of the effective date ordered by the relevant state commission; provided, however, that PSCo will promptly seek FERC approval or acceptance of such rate changes and if FERC disallows any portion of the rate change, the disallowance will be reflected in the formula rate calculations retroactively to such effective date.
9. Prepayments in rate base shall exclude the following prepaid items: a. transmission expense; b. interest expense; c. gross receipts tax; d. retail regulatory fee; and e. other retail related prepayments.
10. The Prepaid Pension Asset balance will be excluded from rate base.
F. Expenses.
1. All transmission-related costs (for both capital items and expenses) recovered through direct assignments of such costs to specific customers (e.g., facilities charges) shall be identified on a workpaper that shall also show that a related revenue credit has been made or that such costs have otherwise been excluded from recovery under the formula rates.
2. Regulatory Commission expense shall include only expenses consistent with Commission regulatory policy and related directly to matters pertaining to transmission service and transmission operations, e.g., transmission rate cases, OATT tariff terms and conditions changes, rule compliance, transmission facility siting cases, or transmission unbundling cases.
3. Depreciation and amortization expenses associated with franchises and consents required only for retail service shall be excluded from recovery under the formula.
4. The allowable amounts recorded in each company’s Account 565 to be included shall be limited to those transmission services associated with the integration of such company’s transmission system and for which access to the associated facilities is available to the PSCo transmission customers of such company without additional charge. Currently, the Account 565 costs associated with only the Holy Cross Tie Agreement will be included in the formula expenses.
5. Account 561 costs shall be recoverable through the formula only to the extent that they exceed in any calendar year the amount of such costs that are deemed to be recovered through Ancillary Service 1 charges, i.e., currently $4,769,960 for PSCo.
6. If an extraordinary (non-recurring) expense would increase the overall Annual Transmission Revenue Requirement (“ATRR”) by more than 3% over the ATRR without the extraordinary expense, the expense will be amortized for formula rate purposes in accordance with the following schedule and for such purposes the unamortized amount will be added to rate base. (New lines will be added to formula to accommodate any such amortization.)
3% to 6% - the amortization period will be 2 years 6% to 9% - the amortization period will be 3 years 9% to 12% - the amortization period will be 4 years over 12% - the amortization period will be 5 years
G. Revenue Credits.
1. The Revenue Credits in the formula rate shall exclude the component “Grandfathered Interzonal Transactions” without prejudice to the right of PSCo to make appropriate filings in the future seeking to include such item, when applicable, as a revenue credit or otherwise to include the effects of such transactions in the formula rate.
2. The formula shall assure that revenue credits are made for all transmission revenues associated with transmission loads that are not otherwise included in the Divisor. Such revenues shall be identified on a workpaper which shall also indicate how the revenue credit has been made in application of the formula.
3. Transmission revenues for transmission services recorded in Account 447 and for which the associated loads are not included in the formula rate Divisor shall also be included as revenue credits.
4. Rent Revenues recorded in Account 454 from facilities classified as administrative and general in nature will be included in the formula and allocated to the transmission function based on the Wages and Salaries allocator.
H. Allocation Factors.
1. Allowable prepayments shall be sub-functionalized between plant-related items and labor-related items. Plant-related items shall be allocated using a net plant allocator. Labor-related items shall be allocated based on functional wage and salary ratios.
2. The Divisor in the formula rate shall be modified to delete the term “Contract Demand from Grandfathered Interzonal Transactions over one year,” without prejudice to the right of PSCo to make appropriate filings in the future seeking to include such item in the Divisor or otherwise to include the effects of such transactions in the formula rates.
3. Account 565 credit to O&M expense shall be 100% allocated to the transmission function.

Section 11.1 Security for Performance. (A) Seller shall establish, fund, and maintain a Security Fund which shall be available (i) to pay any amount due PSCo pursuant to this WESA, (ii) to provide PSCo security that Seller will construct the Facility to meet the Construction Milestones, and (iii) to pay any amount due PSCo pursuant to the Interconnection Agreement. The Security Fund shall provide security to PSCo to cover damages PSCo may incur should the Facility not achieve the Commercial Operation Date or thereafter not operate in accordance with this WESA. Seller agrees to establish the Security Fund no later than the later of (i) forty-five (45) days after the satisfaction or waiver of the CPUC approval referenced in Section 18.1(B), or (ii) forty-five (45) days after the execution of this WESA and (notwithstanding the Damage Cap) to maintain the Security Fund at the required level throughout the remainder of the Term of this WESA, to be available and used as provided in Section 11.1(B) below. Seller shall initially establish the Security Fund at a level of one million seven hundred thousand dollars ($1,700,000) and shall maintain the Security Fund at the lesser of one million seven hundred thousand dollars ($1,700,000) or the then applicable Damage Cap. Seller shall replenish the Security Fund within thirty (30) days following any draw on the Security Fund by PSCo to a level equal to the lesser of (i) one million seven hundred thousand dollars ($1,700,000), and (ii) the then applicable Damage Cap less the aggregate amount of draws on the Security Fund to date (B) In addition to any other remedy available to it, PSCo may, at such times before or after termination of this WESA, draw from the Security Fund appropriate amounts in order to recover such sums or amounts owing to it pursuant to this WESA or the Interconnection Agreement, including, without limitation, any damages due to PSCo. PSCo may, in its sole discretion, draw all or any part of the amounts due to it from any form of security to the extent available pursuant to this Section 11.1, and from all such forms, and in any sequence PSCo may select. Any failure to draw upon the Security Fund or other security for any damages or other amounts due to PSCo shall not prejudice PSCo?s rights to recover such damages or amounts in any other manner. (C) The Security Fund shall be maintained at Seller?s expense, shall be originated by or deposited in a financial institution or company (?Issuer?) acceptable to PSCo, and shall be in the form of one or more of the following instruments. Seller may change the form of the Security Fund at any time and from time to time on reasonable prior notice to PSCo, but the Security Fund must at all times be comprised of one or any combination of the following: (1) An irrevocable standby letter of credit in form and substance acceptable to PSCo from an Issuer with an unsecured bond rating of A- or better (as determined by at least two (2) rating agencies, one of which must be either Standard & Poor?s or Moody?s) (or if either one or both are not available, ratings from alternate rating sources acceptable to PSCo). In addition, if the rating of the Issuer is A-, the Issuer cannot be on negative credit watch. Security provided in this form shall be consistent with this WESA, and shall include a provision for at least thirty (30) days

The form of such letter of credit must meet PSCo?s requirements to ensure that claims or draws can be made unilaterally by PSCo in accordance with the terms of this WESA. This revised agreement for interconnection service (“Interconnection Agreement”), dated as of this 18th day of March 2005, is entered into by and between Public Service Company of Colorado (“Provider”), and Ridge Crest Wind Partners, LLC (“Customer”), may hereinafter be referred to individually as a “Party” and collectively as the “Parties”. Provider agrees to furnish, and Customer agrees to purchase, the Interconnection Service provided for herein pursuant to the terms and conditions of (1) this Interconnection Agreement, and (2) the open access transmission tariff applicable to Provider's transmission system that is on file with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, as it may be amended from time to time or superseded (the "Tariff"). The Tariff is incorporated herein and made a part hereof.
WHEREAS, Customer desires to construct and operate an electric generating plant to be located nearby the Public Service Company of Colorado Peetz Substation and described more fully herein, identified as the “Facility,” and to interconnect the Facility with Provider’s electric system; and
WHEREAS, Provider is willing to provide Interconnection Service to Customer, and Customer desires to purchase such Interconnection Service from Provider, under the terms and conditions specified herein.
WHEREAS, Provider and Customer entered into an Agreement for Interconnection Service effective October 1, 2001, (the “Agreement”), accepted for filing by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission in Docket Nos. ER03-154-000 and as restated in ER05-830-000;
WHEREAS, the Parties desire to amend the Agreement to reflect termination of the Western Electricity Coordinating Council (“WECC”) Reliability Management System (“RMS”) procedures, and to restate the Agreement to comply with FERC eTariff filing procedures;
NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants herein contained, the sufficiency and adequacy of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties agree to the following:
Article 1 -- Definitions Capitalized terms used in this Interconnection Agreement shall have the meanings set forth above, in this Article, or as set forth in the Tariff, whether in the singular or the plural or in the present or past tense. Customer’s Interconnection Facilities are identified and described in Exhibit A.

Article 2 -- Scope, Term and Termination 2.1 Scope of Interconnection Agreement.
(a) General. The Provider shall provide Interconnection Service to the Customer in accordance with this Interconnection Agreement. This Interconnection Agreement amends and restates and supersedes in its entirety the agreement between Public Service Company of Colorado and Ridge Crest Wind Partners, LLC for Interconnection Service, dated March 18, 2005.
(b) Limited Scope of Interconnection Agreement. This Interconnection Agreement sets forth only those terms and conditions necessary to govern Provider's provision of Interconnection Service to Customer. Although Provider intends to file this Interconnection Agreement with the FERC as a service agreement under the Tariff, this Interconnection Agreement does not in itself entitle Customer to receive any services under the Tariff other than the Interconnection Service provided for herein: any other services that Customer may require must be separately arranged under the Tariff in accordance with its terms and conditions and paid for by Customer or other beneficiary of such services. Provider is under no obligation to provide services under this Interconnection Agreement other than Interconnection Service. Likewise, the establishment of an interconnection under this Interconnection Agreement does not in itself entitle Customer to obtain any services from Provider that may be subject to the jurisdiction of the CPUC: Customer must arrange for any such services in accordance with Provider's applicable tariffs, or make other appropriate arrangements with Provider for such services.
(c) Facilities Served. The scope of the Interconnection Service provided hereunder is based on Customer's description of its Facility (including Customer's Interconnection Facilities), as set forth in Exhibit A. In the event that Customer proposes to increase the output of the Facility or make any other material change or modification to the configuration or operation of the Facility or the Customer’s Interconnection Facilities, the Customer shall first notify Provider of such proposal, and the Parties shall negotiate in good faith in an effort to amend this Interconnection Agreement to accommodate such proposed change. In the event that the Parties are unable to agree to appropriate modifications to this Interconnection Agreement, Provider will unilaterally file with FERC an amendment to this Interconnection Agreement following those procedures applicable to unexecuted service agreements set out in Section 15.3 of the Tariff. In no event will Customer increase the output of the Facility or otherwise make a material change in the configuration or operation of the Facility prior to reaching of a mutual agreement with Provider or before FERC accepts amendments to this Interconnection Agreement to accommodate Customer’s proposed changes.
2.2 Term and Termination. Subject to any necessary FERC authorization, this Interconnection Agreement shall become effective as of October 1, 2001. Unless terminated earlier in accordance with Section 2.3 below, it shall remain in effect for a period of 25 years.
2.3 Early Termination. Notwithstanding the term specified in Section 2.2 and subject to the requirements of this Section 2.3, this Interconnection Agreement may be terminated early in the following circumstances: (1) by the Customer upon one hundred eighty days written notice for any reason; and (2) by the Provider in the event of any material breach of this Interconnection Agreement by the Customer; provided that Provider has first obtained any necessary authorization from FERC to terminate service. In the event that either Party seeks to terminate this Interconnection Agreement early, Customer shall be obligated to pay to Provider an early termination fee equal to the amount of the Security Fund as described further in Exhibit C. If Customer fails to make such payment, Provider may immediately draw upon the Security Fund (Exhibit C) established in accordance with Article 6, and take any other appropriate legal action, to obtain recovery of the early termination fee.
The early termination fee that Customer is obligated to pay shall be reduced as appropriate, (i) if the Provider may reasonably charge or recover from a third party the costs formerly charged or recovered from Customer under this Agreement, or (ii) if the Provider utilizes the Interconnection Facilities in connection with its own business, or (iii) if Provider may recover salvage value from the Interconnection Facilities that are no longer useful.
2.4 Survival. Certain provisions of this Interconnection Agreement shall continue in effect after termination of this Interconnection Agreement to give full effect to its terms. Such provisions include, but are not necessarily limited to, those relating to early terminations, Customer’s payment for installation, operation, and maintenance of Interconnection Facilities, and, as applicable, to provide for disconnection of the Facility from the Provider electric system, final billings and adjustments related to the period prior to termination, and payment of any money due and owing either Party pursuant to this Interconnection Agreement. Upon termination of this Interconnection Agreement, Provider may, at its sole discretion and Customer’s expense, remove Provider’s Interconnection Facilities.
2.5 Completion of Studies and Third Party Arrangements. Provider’s provision of Interconnection Service under this Agreement is contingent upon the completion of (i) all necessary work to evaluate the proposed interconnection, demonstrating the cost and feasibility of the proposed interconnection, and (ii) any necessary arrangements with the Western Area Power Administration to establish the proposed interconnection satisfactory to Provider and Customer.
Article 3 -- Facility Interconnection and Metering 3.1 Summary Description. Exhibit A, which is attached hereto and made a part hereof, provides a complete description of the Facility, including Customer's Interconnection Facilities, including identification of the equipment and components which make up the Facility. Exhibit A also includes a scaled map and one-line diagram that identifies the Facility’s location, the location of Customer's Interconnection Facilities, the location of any facilities used to provide retail service to customer, including any associated disconnect devices, and the Interconnection Point(s).
3.2 Design and Operation of the Facility. Customer shall design, construct, operate, and maintain the Facility and Customer’s Interconnection Facilities in accordance with Good Utility Practice and the Interconnection Guidelines.
3.3 Provider’s Interconnection Facilities. Provider shall design, construct, operate, maintain, and own Provider’s Interconnection Facilities and shall use due diligence to have such facilities constructed and available for service by October 1, 2001. Customer shall reimburse Provider for costs associated with the design, construction, operation, maintenance, and ownership of the Provider’s Interconnection Facilities as set forth in Section 8.1. Exhibit B, which is attached hereto and made a part hereof, provides a complete description of Provider’s Interconnection Facilities, including identification of the components which make up Provider’s Interconnection Facilities and a one-line diagram of such facilities, the Interconnection Point(s), and metering for the Facility.
3.4 Customer’s Interconnection Facilities and Protective Systems. Customer shall design, construct, operate, maintain and own, each at Customer’s sole expense, Customer’s Interconnection Facilities, and operate such facilities in a manner that protects Provider’s electric system and Provider’s Interconnection Facilities from transients, faults, and other operating contingencies occurring at or caused by the Facility. Design and specification of protective relaying, alarming, fault recording, control, metering, and related systems for generators, high voltage switch gear, stepup transformers, and plant service transformers (when connected to the high voltage bus), shall be subject to Provider’s review and approval, which approval shall not be unreasonably withheld or delayed. All protective systems must be in compliance with the Interconnection Guidelines.
3.5 Protection of the Provider's Electric System. The Facility shall satisfy all the requirements of the Interconnection Guidelines and the requirements set forth in this Article 3.5:
(a) The Facility shall be designed to generate and deliver power and energy into the Provider's electric system as three-phase alternating current with a nominal frequency of sixty (60) hertz and a nominal voltage of 115kV at the Interconnection Point(s). Customer shall cause its deliveries of power and energy to be consistent with the Interconnection Guidelines with respect to maintenance of frequency and voltage stability and avoidance of voltage transients. The Facility shall be capable of operating on automatic voltage regulation pursuant to WECC or NERC requirements. In accordance with the Interconnection Guidelines, the Facility shall be equipped to provide adequate voltage and frequency regulation to operate in parallel with the Provider’s electric system without causing a degradation of service on Provider’s electric system or the Western Interconnection. (b) Customer agrees that Provider shall have the right, exercisable at the sole determination of Provider exercised in accordance with Good Utility Practice, to disconnect the Facility from the Provider’s electric system: (1) during an Emergency; or (2) if such disconnection is necessary to prevent damage to Provider’s equipment or the equipment of its customers, or to maintain electric service to its customers; or (3) if such disconnection is required to permit (a) repairs to the Provider's electric system, (b) new construction, or (c) the connection of other lines, customers, or generators; or (4) if such disconnection is required for equipment maintenance or to facilitate restoration of line outages; or (5) if such disconnection is necessary for the operation of the Provider's electric system consistent with Good Utility Practice; or (6) in the event Customer tampers with Provider’s Interconnection Facilities; or (7) in the event that Customer increases the output of the Facility or substantially changes or modifies the configuration or operation of the Facility without Provider's consent; or (8) in the event that Customer fails to provide Provider with access to the Customer’s Interconnection Facilities adequate for Provider to perform all inspections, maintenance, service, and operational reviews as may be appropriate and necessary to facilitate the performance of this Interconnection Agreement. In the event Provider disconnects the Facility from Provider’s electric system, Provider shall restore the interconnection as soon as practicable following cure of the condition that gave rise to the disconnection. Provider shall determine, in its sole discretion exercised in accordance with Good Utility Practice, whether and when the condition that gave rise to the disconnection has been cured.
(c) Provider shall provide the Customer with oral notification that is prompt under the circumstances of an Emergency that may reasonably be expected to affect the Customer's operation of the Facility, to the extent the Provider is aware of the Emergency. The Customer shall provide the Provider with oral notification that is prompt under the circumstances of an Emergency which may reasonably be expected to affect the Provider’s electric system, to the extent the Customer is aware of the Emergency. To the extent the Party becoming aware of an Emergency is aware of the facts of the Emergency, such oral notification shall describe the Emergency, the extent of the damage or deficiency, its anticipated duration, and the corrective action taken and/or to be taken. In all instances, oral notification shall be followed as soon as practicable with written notice.
In the event of an Emergency, the Party becoming aware of the Emergency may, in accordance with Good Utility Practice and using its reasonable judgment, take such action as is reasonable and necessary to prevent, avoid, or mitigate injury, danger, and loss. In the event the Customer has identified an Emergency involving the Provider’s electric system, the Customer shall obtain the consent of Provider personnel prior to manually performing any switching operations unless, in the Customer's reasonable judgment, immediate action is required.
The Provider may, consistent with Good Utility Practice, take whatever actions or inactions the Provider deems necessary during an Emergency in order to: (1) preserve public health and safety; (2) preserve the reliability of the Provider's electric system and Provider’s Interconnection Facilities; (3) limit or prevent damage; and (4) expedite restoration of service. The Provider shall use reasonable efforts to minimize the effect of such actions or inactions on the Customer’s Facility.
The Customer may, consistent with Good Utility Practice, take whatever actions or inactions with regard to the Facility or any Customer Interconnection Facilities the Customer deems necessary during an Emergency in order to: (1) preserve public health and safety; (2) preserve the reliability of the Facility and Customer’s Interconnection Facilities; (3) limit or prevent damage; and (4) expedite restoration of service. The Customer shall use reasonable efforts to minimize the effect of such actions or inactions on the Provider’s electric system.
(d) If any disconnection of the Facility is caused or made necessary by the operation or maintenance of the Facility or any other reason within Customer’s control, Customer shall reimburse Provider for Provider’s actual cost (including any out-of-pocket expenses as well as allowable overhead) incurred for the actions necessary for Provider to disconnect and reconnect its system to the Facility.
3.6 [Reserved]
3.7 Communication Equipment. Customer shall provide and maintain a dial-up telephone circuit for direct voice communications between the PCC and Facility operations.
3.8 Transmission Line Relaying. Provider shall install and test protective relaying associated with its transmission line or lines, according to the Interconnection Guidelines. Customer shall be responsible for procuring, installing, and wiring all cable into the termination block demarcation points on Provider’s panels which are part of Provider’s Interconnection Facilities at Customer’s Interconnection Facility. Customer shall be responsible for all wiring to Provider’s panels at Customer’s Interconnection Facility. Customer shall use shielded cable that meets Provider’s specifications for all circuits between Customer’s 115kV breaker and Provider’s panels at Customer’s Interconnection Facility. Any wiring errors that are encountered shall be corrected by Customer with due diligence. Customer’s 115kV breaker shall meet Provider’s specifications as set forth in the Interconnection Guidelines.
3.9 Notice of System Changes. Provider and Customer shall provide each other with timely notice, pursuant to Article 16, of any changes in their respective systems or facilities that may affect the proper coordination of safety devices on the two systems, and shall notify each other immediately in the event that hazardous or unsafe conditions associated with operations pursuant to this Interconnection Agreement are discovered to exist. Changes to Customer’s Interconnection Facilities that may affect the proper coordination of safety devices on the Provider’s electric system cannot be made other than with the express prior written approval of Provider, which shall not unreasonably be withheld.
3.10 Relay Trip Test. Each year, Customer’s interconnection relay equipment and generator control equipment shall be tested, at Customer’s expense, by a qualified power system protection and control contractor (which may include Customer’s qualified technician) to demonstrate proper protective equipment activation and interlocks. No fewer than thirty (30) days prior to the scheduled test date, Customer shall notify Provider of the protection and control contractor selected by Customer and coordinate the test date with Provider. If Customer fails to perform such test within forty-five (45) days after the anniversary of the date service commences under this Interconnection Agreement, Provider, may, at its sole discretion, physically interrupt the flow of energy from the Facility until such test has been completed. Provider may require Customer to reschedule the demonstration test if Customer fails to notify Provider of the scheduled test date. Provider, at its sole discretion, may be present to witness testing of equipment. Customer’s protection and control contractor shall document the demonstration test in a report certified by qualified personnel with experience in power system protection and control. A copy of the test report shall be provided to Provider within twenty-one (21) days after testing has been completed. Provider may require Customer to reschedule such test if the demonstration of such test or reported test results do not conform or adhere to the Interconnection Guidelines. The Parties will confer in an attempt to schedule tests in a manner that will not interfere with the Facility’s commercial operations.
3.11 Relay Calibration. Every three years, Customer’s interconnection relay equipment and generator control equipment shall be calibrated by a qualified power system protection and control contractor (which may include Customer’s qualified technician). No fewer than thirty (30) days prior to the scheduled calibration date, Customer shall notify Provider of the protection and control contractor selected by Customer and coordinate the calibration date with Provider. If Customer fails to perform such calibration within forty-five (45) days after the anniversary of the date service commences under Article 4 of this Interconnection Agreement, Provider, may at its sole discretion, physically interrupt the flow of energy from the Facility until such calibration has been completed. Provider may require Customer to reschedule the calibration date if Customer fails to notify Provider of the scheduled date of calibration. Provider, at its sole discretion, may be present to witness calibration of equipment. Customer’s protection and control contractor shall document the calibration in a report certified by qualified personnel with experience in power system protection and control. A copy of the report shall be provided to Provider within twenty-one (21) days after calibration has been completed. Provider may require Customer to reschedule such calibration if the demonstration of such calibration or reported calibration results do not conform or adhere to the Interconnection Guidelines. The Parties will confer in an attempt to schedule calibration tests in a manner that will not interfere with the Facility’s commercial operations.
3.12 Customer’s Modifications to Equipment. If Customer proposes changes or modifications to the Facility generator control and protective equipment or interlocks, Customer shall notify Provider, in writing, of such proposed changes or modifications at least ninety (90) days prior to the planned implementation of such changes or modifications. Customer’s notice to Provider shall include three (3) sets of drawings and specifications of such changes or modifications for Provider’s review and approval. Provider shall provide Customer with a written response, indicating approval (which shall not unreasonably be withheld) or proposed revisions of such drawings and specifications, within thirty (30) days of receipt, together with a description of any basis upon which Provider considers Customer’s drawings or specifications to be unacceptable. Provider agrees to expedite this procedure when Customer desires to make changes or modifications to failed equipment. If at any time, Provider observes any generator control or protective equipment which appears to have been changed or failed, Provider shall have the right, at its discretion, to disconnect the Facility from the Provider electric system and may require, at Customer’s expense, a new calibration and activation test of Customer’s generator control equipment or protective equipment after such equipment has been corrected or repaired.
3.13 Access to Facility. Appropriate representatives of Provider shall at all reasonable times, including weekends and nights, and with fourteen (14) days prior notice, have access to the Facility, including the control room and Customer’s Interconnection Facilities, to take readings and to perform all inspections, maintenance, service, and operational reviews as may be appropriate or necessary to facilitate the performance of this Interconnection Agreement. While at the Facility, such representatives shall announce their presence to Facility control room staff and observe such safety precautions as may be required by Customer and shall conduct themselves in a manner that will not interfere with the operation of the Facility. Provider normally will request access to perform routine tasks only during regular business hours, but Provider reserves its right under this Interconnection Agreement to request access at any time as necessary.
3.14 Metering Devices.
(a) All Metering Devices used to measure the net power and energy generated by Customer under this Interconnection Agreement shall be owned, installed, and maintained by Provider. All Metering Devices used to provide data to the Control Area shall be sealed and only Provider shall break the seal when such Metering Devices are to be inspected and tested or adjusted in accordance with this Article. In the event a Metering Device is not physically located so as to measure power and energy at the Interconnection Points, Provider shall adjust the reading of such Metering Device so as to account for any transformation or interconnection losses between the location of the meter and the Interconnection Points. The number, type, and location of such Metering Devices shall be specified by Provider. Provider agrees to allow Customer read only access to kwh billing meter recorder.
(b) Provider shall inspect and test all Metering Devices upon installation and at least annually thereafter. Provider shall provide Customer with fourteen (14) days advance notice of, and permit a representative of Customer to witness and verify, such inspections and tests, provided, however, that Customer shall not unreasonably interfere with or disrupt the activities of Provider and shall comply with all of Provider’s safety standards. Upon request by Customer, Provider shall perform additional inspections or tests of any Metering Device and shall permit a qualified representative of Customer to inspect or witness the testing of any Metering Device, provided, however, that Customer shall comply with all of Provider’s safety standards. The actual additional expense of any inspection or testing shall be borne by Customer. If requested by Customer in writing, Provider shall provide copies of any inspection or testing reports to Customer.
(c) Customer may elect to install and maintain, at its own expense, backup metering devices (“Customer’s BackUp Metering”) in addition to those installed and maintained by Provider, which installation and maintenance shall be in a manner acceptable to Provider. Customer’s Back-Up Metering shall not be installed in the voltage transformer (VT) and current transformer (CT) secondary circuits that serve the Provider’s revenue metering. Customer, at its own expense, shall inspect and test Customer’s BackUp Metering upon installation and at least annually thereafter. Customer shall provide Provider with fourteen (14) days advance notice of, and permit a representative of Provider to witness and verify, such inspections and tests, provided, however, that Provider shall not unreasonably interfere with or disrupt the activities of Customer and shall comply with all of Customer’s safety standards. Upon request by Provider, Customer shall perform additional inspections or tests of Customer’s BackUp Metering and shall permit a qualified representative of Provider to inspect or witness the testing of Customer’s BackUp Metering, provided, however, that Provider shall comply with all of Customer’s safety standards. The actual expense of any such requested additional inspection or testing shall be borne by Provider, unless, upon such inspection or testing, Customer’s BackUp Metering is found to register inaccurately by more than the allowable limits established in this Article, in which event the expense of the requested additional inspection or testing shall be borne by Customer.
(d) If any Metering Devices, or Customer’s BackUp Metering, are found to be defective or inaccurate, they shall be adjusted, repaired, replaced, and/or recalibrated as near as practicable to a condition of zero error by the Party owning such defective or inaccurate device and at that Party’s expense.
(e) If a Metering Device, or Customer’s Back-Up Metering, fails to register, or if the measurement made by a Metering Device, or Customer’s Back-Up Metering, is found upon testing to be inaccurate by more than one percent (1.0%), an adjustment shall be made correcting all measurements by the inaccurate or defective Metering Device, or Customer’s Back-Up Metering, for both the amount of the inaccuracy and the period of the inaccuracy, in the following manner:
(f) In the event that Provider’s Metering Device is found to be defective or inaccurate, the Parties shall use Customer’s Back-up Metering, if installed, to determine the amount of such inaccuracy, provided, however, that Customer’s BackUp Metering has been tested and maintained in accordance with the provisions of this Article. In the event that Customer’s Backup Metering is also found to be inaccurate by more than one percent (1.0%), the Parties shall estimate the amount of the necessary adjustment on the basis of deliveries of net power and energy from the Facility during periods of similar operating conditions when the Metering Device was registering accurately. The adjustment shall be made for the period during which inaccurate measurements were made.
(g) In the event that the Parties cannot agree on the actual period during which the inaccurate measurements were made, the period during which the measurements are to be adjusted shall be the shorter of (1) the last onehalf of the period from the last previous test of the Metering Device to the test that found the Metering Device to be defective or inaccurate, or (2) the one hundred eighty (180) days immediately preceding the test that found the Metering Device to be defective or inaccurate.
(h) A SCADA remote terminal unit (“RTU”) will be specified, procured and installed at Peetz Substation by Provider at Customer’s sole expense, to gather accumulated and instantaneous data to be telemetered to the PCC through the use of dedicated point- to- point data circuits. 3.15 Reliability Standards. Provider and Customer are each a Registered Entity with the WECC. (a) Customer shall be responsible for compliance with all NERC and WECC mandatory Reliability Standards applicable to the Facility, and Provider shall be responsible for compliance with all NERC and WECC mandatory Reliability Standards applicable to the Interconnection Facility. In addition, Customer shall operate the Facility in accordance with applicable provisions of the Interconnection Guidelines. (b) Each Party shall be responsible for the costs of compliance with such Reliability Standards for the respective facilities they own, including (i) costs associated with modifying their respective facilities or systems to comply with changes in such Reliability Standards, and (ii) any financial penalties for non-compliance. The Parties agree to share data or documentation as may be required to demonstrate compliance with Reliability Standards where an individual Party has possession of data or documentation necessary for the other Party to demonstrate compliance. (c) To the extent that Customer contributes in whole or in part to actions which result in monetary penalties being assessed to Provider by such agencies for lack of compliance with Reliability Standards, Customer shall reimburse Provider for its proportional share of such monetary penalties. In the event of a dispute between the Parties regarding Customer’s share of such monetary penalties, the dispute shall be subject to the provisions of Article 15 herein.
Article 4 -- Commencement of Service Service under this Interconnection Agreement shall commence on the later of (1) October 1, 2001, or (2) the date on which construction of Provider’s Interconnection Facilities is completed to Provider’s reasonable satisfaction, or (3) such other date as this Interconnection Agreement is permitted to become effective by the Commission.
Article 5 -- Operations and Maintenance 5.1 Operations. The Parties shall operate and control their respective systems, facilities, and equipment (1) in a safe and reliable manner; (2) in accordance with Good Utility Practice; (3) in accordance with applicable operational and/or reliability criteria, protocols, and directives, including those of NERC and WECC; and (4) in accordance with the provisions of this Interconnection Agreement.
5.2 Maintenance. The Parties shall coordinate in advance modifications, maintenance, and outages which impact use of the Interconnection Facilities to the extent such coordination is reasonably practicable and is consistent with Good Utility Practice and other applicable provisions of this Interconnection Agreement.
5.3 Facility Operation. Customer shall staff, control, and operate the Facility in a manner that is, at all times, consistent with the requirements set forth in this Interconnection Agreement. Customer shall, in a timely manner, inform the PCC of any significant changes in the Facility’s operating status. 5.4 Outage Reporting. Customer shall comply with all current Provider, NERC, and WECC generating unit outage reporting requirements, as they may be revised from time to time, and as they apply to the Facility. When Forced Outages occur, Customer shall notify the PCC of the existence, nature, and expected duration of the Forced Outage as soon as practical, but in no event later than one (1) hour after the Forced Outage occurs. Customer shall immediately inform the PCC of changes in the expected duration of the Forced Outage unless relieved of this obligation by the PCC for the duration of each Forced Outage.
Article 6 -- Security for Performance and Early Termination 6.1 Security for Performance.
(a) Subject to Section 6.1(f), Customer shall establish, fund, and maintain a Security Fund which shall be available at Provider’s discretion, pursuant to this Article 6, to secure its payment obligation to Provider pursuant to this Interconnection Agreement. The amount of the Security Fund is listed in Exhibit C attached hereto. Unless creditworthiness is established in accordance with Section 6.1(f), Customer shall establish and maintain the Security Fund effective upon the expiration of the WESA (as defined in Section 6.2 below).
(b) The Security Fund shall be maintained at Customer’s expense, shall be originated by or deposited in a financial institution or company acceptable to Provider, and shall be in the form of one of the following instruments:
(1) An unconditional and irrevocable standby letter of credit, in form and substance acceptable to Provider, from an entity with an unsecured (i.e., not supported by third party credit enhancement) bond rating equivalent to A- or better as determined by at least two (2) rating agencies, one of which must be either Standard & Poor’s or Moody’s, or, if either or both are not available to provide a bond rating, ratings from two alternative rating sources acceptable to Provider. Security provided in this form shall be consistent with this Interconnection Agreement and include a provision for thirty (30) days advance notice to Provider of any expiration of the security so as to allow Provider sufficient time to exercise its rights under said security if Customer fails to extend or replace the security; or
(2) An alternative form of security acceptable to Provider and consistent with the applicable provisions of the Tariff.
(c) If security in the form of an unconditional and irrevocable letter of credit is utilized by Customer to fund the Security Fund, the form of such letter must meet Provider’s requirements to ensure that claims or draw-downs can be made in accordance with the terms of this Interconnection Agreement. Such security must be issued for a minimum term of three hundred sixty (360) days. Customer shall effect the renewal or extension of the security for another minimum term of three hundred and sixty (360) days, or for the remainder of the Term of this Interconnection Agreement, whichever period is shorter, no later than thirty (30) days prior to the expiration date of the security. If Customer fails to affect the renewal of such security as required under this Article, Provider shall have the right to draw immediately upon the security and to place the amounts so drawn in an escrow account in accordance with this Article until and unless Customer shall provide a substitute form of such security meeting the requirements of this Article.
(d) With respect to any escrow account opened as security for Customer’s obligations hereunder, Provider shall establish at Customer’s cost and with Customer’s funds an interest-bearing escrow account in the name of Provider. Such escrow account may be drawn upon by Provider to satisfy any unsatisfied obligations hereunder that the Security Fund is intended to secure. If Customer’s obligation to provide security hereunder expires, Provider shall return the balance, including principle and interest thereupon, in such escrow account to Customer. At such times as the balance in the escrow account exceeds the amount of Customer’s obligation to provide security hereunder, Provider shall remit to Customer any excess in the escrow account above Customer’s obligations. Customer may obtain the return of such escrow account at any time by providing to Provider a substitute form of security in the same amount as the escrow account and meeting the appropriate criteria specified in this Article.
(e) At the completion of all of Customer’s obligations under this Interconnection Agreement, Customer shall be entitled to the Security Fund and accumulated interest if any funds remain in the Security Fund and if such remaining funds are not owed to Provider under this Interconnection Agreement at such time.
(f) Customer will not be required to establish and maintain the Security Fund if it is creditworthy or if it provides a guarantee (in a form acceptable to Provider) from a creditworthy entity. For purposes of establishing creditworthiness, Provider will deem an entity creditworthy provided that (a) its long-term unsecured bonds (or if none, other unsecured senior debt) are rated by at least one of the major rating agencies (Standard & Poors, Moody’s, or Fitch) and (b) no rating by such agencies are (i) below investment grade or (ii) at investment grade but with a negative outlook. In the event that Customer, or its guarantor, becomes uncreditworthy, as based on these criteria, Customer shall, within seventy-two (72) hours of becoming aware that it or its guarantor has become uncreditworthy, establish the Security Fund required by this Article 6. Provider shall, if it becomes aware that Customer or its guarantor has become uncreditworthy, promptly notify Customer of such occurrence, provided that Customer shall have an independent obligation to establish the Security Fund when it first becomes aware that it or its guarantor has become uncreditworthy, and provided further that Provider’s failure to become independently aware of Customer’s or its guarantor’s uncreditworthiness or to notify Customer of such occurrence shall not excuse or delay Customer’s obligation to establish the Security Fund as required by this Article 6. If Customer, or its guarantor, subsequently become creditworthy after a loss of creditworthiness, provider will, within seventy-two (72) hours of receiving notice from Customer that it or its guarantor has become creditworthy, return to Customer the funds in the Security Fund together with any interest accumulated on such funds while part of the Security Fund, if any.
6.2 Provisions Relating to Customer’s Power Sale Agreement to Provider. Provider and Customer are parties to a Wind Energy Supply Agreement (“WESA”) dated the date hereof, pursuant to which Customer shall supply power and energy for a term ending on November 30, 2016 (the “WESA Term”). During the WESA Term, the following special terms shall apply to this Agreement:
(a) During the WESA Term, the Security Fund that Customer is providing in accordance with Section 11.1 of the WESA (included as part of Exhibit F hereto) shall be deemed to satisfy the security requirements set forth in Article 6 of this Agreement.
(b) During the WESA Term, the Damages Cap, as defined in Section 1.12 and applied in Section 11.3 of the WESA (both sections included as part of Exhibit F hereto), shall apply to any and all liability that Customer may have to Provider under this Agreement.
Article 7 -- Force Majeure The provisions of Section 10.1 of the Tariff shall apply for Force Majeure for Interconnection Service under this Interconnection Agreement except, for purposes of this Interconnection Agreement, a Curtailment (as defined in the Tariff) will not be deemed to constitute an event of Force Majeure.
Article 8 -- Charges for Service 8.1 Facilities Charge. Upon commencement of service under this Interconnection Agreement as set forth in Article 4, Customer shall pay Provider the monthly Facilities Charge. Such Facilities Charge is a negotiated amount and is set forth in the Rate Schedule attached to this Interconnection Agreement as Exhibit E. The Facilities Charge is intended to provide Provider with a contribution to the costs it incurs in planning, constructing, owning, operating, maintaining, repairing, and replacing Provider's Interconnection Facilities, including the initial study costs incurred in determining the adequacy and reliability of the interconnected system.
8.2 Retail Charges. Customer’s payment of the Direct Assignment Facilities Charge shall not preclude Provider from recovering any charges that are subject to the jurisdiction of the CPUC, even if associated with the interconnection provided for in this Interconnection Agreement (e.g., metering costs associated with obtaining retail service).
Article 9 -- Billing and Payment The provisions of Article 7 of the Tariff shall apply for billing and payment for Interconnection Service under this Interconnection Agreement.
Article 10 -- Regulation and Modification of Rates 10.1 Regulation of Rates. This Interconnection Agreement is subject to the jurisdiction of the FERC, and its effectiveness is contingent upon its approval or acceptance for filing by FERC. It is the intention of the Parties that this Interconnection Agreement shall be filed with FERC as a service agreement under the Tariff.
10.2 Modifications to Rates Provider reserves its rights under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act to unilaterally make application to FERC for modification of the rates, terms, conditions, classification of service, rule, or regulation for any service Provider provides under this Interconnection Agreement and the attachments hereto over which FERC has jurisdiction. Customer reserves its rights under Section 206 of the Federal Power Act to unilaterally make application to FERC for modification of the rates, terms, conditions, classification of service, rule, or regulation for any service provided under this Interconnection Agreement and the attachments hereto over which FERC has jurisdiction. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Parties agree that it is their intent that the Facilities Charge specified in Exhibit E will be fixed for the term of this Agreement, and shall not be adjusted for any reason. Accordingly, the Parties agree that neither Party will file, under Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act, as applicable, to change the Facilities Charges set forth in Exhibit E. The standard for review for changes to the Facilities Charge under this Agreement, whether proposed by a non-party or the Commission acting sua sponte, shall be the “public interest” standard of review set forth in United Gas Pipe Line Co. v. Mobile Gas Service Corp., 350 U.S. 332 (1956) and Federal Power Commission v. Sierra Pacific Power Co., 330 U.S. 348 (1956) (commonly referred to as the “Mobile-Sierra Doctrine”).
10.3 State Approvals. The establishment of the Interconnection contemplated by this Interconnection Agreement may also require a certificate of public convenience and necessity from the Public Utilities Commission of Colorado, and other siting approvals. Provider shall not be obligated to construct Provider’s Interconnection Facilities and provide Interconnection Service under this Interconnection Agreement prior to the receipt of all such necessary State approvals.
Article 11 -- Assignment Neither Party shall voluntarily assign its rights nor delegate its duties under this Interconnection Agreement, or any part of such rights or duties, without the written consent of the other Party, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld, except in connection with the sale, merger, or transfer of a substantial portion of its properties (or in the case of Provider, its transmission facilities) including the Interconnection Facilities which it owns so long as the assignee in such a sale, merger, or transfer assumes directly all rights, duties and obligations arising under this Interconnection Agreement and such assignor shall be, without further action, released from its obligation hereunder. Any such assignment or delegation made without such written consent shall be null and void. In addition, Provider shall be entitled to assign this Interconnection Agreement to any affiliate or to a Regional Transmission Organization without obtaining the consent of Customer.
Notwithstanding the foregoing, Customer may assign this Interconnection Agreement (and shall be, without further action, released from obligation hereunder) without Provider’s prior consent to any future owner of the Facility, provided that the new owner assumes and complies with all the provisions of this Interconnection Agreement. In addition and notwithstanding the foregoing, Customer or its assignee may assign this Interconnection Agreement, without Provider’s prior consent, to the persons, entities or institutions providing financing or refinancing for the development, design, construction or operation of the Facility.
Article 12 -- Insurance Without limiting any obligations or liabilities under this Interconnection Agreement, the Customer shall, at their own expense, provide and maintain in effect for the life of this Interconnection Agreement Commercial General Liability (GCL) insurance coverage (in any combination of primary and excess layers) in the minimum amount of Five million dollars ($5,000,000).
Article 13 -- Indemnity and Liability 13.1 Indemnity. The provisions of Section 10.2 of the Tariff shall apply for Indemnity under this Interconnection Agreement.
13.2 Limitation on Liability. Neither Party shall be liable in statute, contract, in tort (including negligence), strict liability, or otherwise to the other Party, its agents, representatives, its affiliated and associated companies, and/or its assigns, for any incidental or consequential loss or damage whatsoever, including, but not limited to, loss of profits or revenue on work not performed, for loss of use of or under-utilization of the other Party's facilities, or loss of use of revenues or loss of anticipated profits, resulting from either Party's performance or non-performance of an obligation imposed on it by this Interconnection Agreement.
Article 14 -- Breach, Cure and Default The provisions of Section 7.3 of the Tariff shall apply for customer default under this Interconnection Agreement.
Article 15 -- Disputes The Dispute Resolution Procedures set out in Article 12 of the Tariff shall apply to any disputes that arise under this Interconnection Agreement.
Article 16 -- Notices and Administrations 16.1 Notices. Any notice or request made to or by either Party regarding this Interconnection Agreement shall be made to the representative of the other Party as set forth in Exhibit D, which is attached hereto and made a part hereof. Any notice, request, consent, or other communication required or authorized under this Interconnection Agreement to be given by one Party to the other Party shall be in writing. It shall either be personally delivered or mailed, postage prepaid, to the representative of said other Party. Any such notice, request, consent, or other communication shall be deemed to be given when delivered or mailed. Real-time or routine communications concerning Facility operations shall be exempt from this Article.
16.2 Exhibit D. Either Party may change the information for their representative set forth in Exhibit D at any time without the approval of the other Party.
Article 17 -- Miscellaneous 17.1. Waiver. Any waiver at any time by either Party of its rights with respect to a default under this Interconnection Agreement, or with respect to any other matters arising in connection with this Interconnection Agreement, shall not be deemed a waiver or continuing waiver with respect to any subsequent default or other matter.
17.2. Governing Law. The validity, interpretation and performance of this Interconnection Agreement and each of its provisions shall be governed by the applicable laws of the State of Colorado, without regard to the conflicts of law provisions.
17.3 Headings. Captions and headings used in this Interconnection Agreement are for ease of reference only and do not constitute a part of this Interconnection Agreement.
17.4 Amendments. This Interconnection Agreement may be amended by and only by a written instrument duly executed by both of the Parties hereto. The effectiveness of such amendments will be contingent upon the FERC's approval or acceptance for filing.
17.5 Entire Agreement. This Interconnection Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties hereto with reference to the subject matter hereof and no change or modification as to any of the provisions hereof shall be binding on either Party unless reduced to writing and approved by the duly authorized officers or agents of the Parties. The terms and conditions of this Interconnection Agreement and every attachment referred to herein shall be amended, as mutually agreed to by the Parties, to comply with changes or alterations made necessary by a valid applicable order of any governmental regulatory authority, or any court, having jurisdiction hereof.
17.6 Binding Effect. This Interconnection Agreement and the rights and obligations hereof, shall be binding upon and shall inure to the benefit of the successors and assigns of the Parties hereto.
17.7 Conflicts. In the event of a conflict between the body of this Interconnection Agreement and any attachment, appendix or exhibit hereto, the terms and provisions of the body of this Interconnection Agreement shall prevail and be deemed to be the final intent of the Parties. In the event any term of this Interconnection Agreement conflicts with the Tariff, the terms of this Interconnection Agreement shall control.
